Ralph Baker's 1925 patent described a method for using electric arc welding to deposit molten metal in superposed layers to create decorative containers and ornamental objects. The process involved manipulating a fusible electrode in spiral and helical patterns to build up three-dimensional forms layer by layer, essentially creating an early form of metal 3D printing.
